\f0\b \cf0 ConTeXt and MetaPost:\
\
\pard\tx560\tx1940\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li1040\ql\qnatural

\f2\b0 \cf0 ConTeXt is a general purpose TeX macro package by Hans Hagen; for some, it will be a serious alternative to LaTeX. See http://www.pragma-ade.com/ for details. \
\
MetaPost is a MetaFont like system by John Hobby which can output postscript and pdf files. The package can be used to draw elaborate postscript illustrations.  See http://cm.bell-labs.com/who/hobby/MetaPost.html for more details.  Interesting metapost examples can be found at many web sites; for instance see  http://www.cs.ucc.ie/~dongen/mpost/mpost.html. TeXShop now supports MetaPost.\
\
Here is a sample MetaPost file:\
\
\pard\tx560\tx1940\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li1040\ql\qnatural

\f3\fs20 \cf0 	prologues:=2;\
	color yellow; yellow = green + red;\
	def star (expr size, n, pos, color)=\
		for a=0 step 360/n until 360:\
			draw (origin -- (size/2,0))\
			rotatedaround (origin, a)\
			shifted pos withcolor color;\
		endfor ;\
	enddef;\
\
	beginfig(-1);\
	pickup pencircle scaled 2mm; star (2cm,5,origin,red);\
	endfig;\
\
	beginfig(2);\
	pickup pencircle scaled 2mm; star (2cm,7,origin,yellow);\
	endfig;\
\
	beginfig(3);\
	pickup pencircle scaled 2mm; star (2cm,11,origin,green);\
	endfig;\
\
	beginfig(4);\
	pickup pencircle scaled 2mm; star (2cm,13,origin,blue);\
	endfig;\
\
	end\
\
\pard\tx560\tx1940\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li1040\ql\qnatural

\f2\fs24 \cf0 Suppose this file is named "metademo.tex." When the file is processed by MetaPost, it will generate four different postscript files, named metademo.ps, metademo.2, metademo.3, metademo.4. These names are determined by the number parameter of "beginfig()." If this number is positive, like beginfig(10), the resulting file will be named metademo.10. If this number is negative, like beginfig(-10), the resulting file will be named metademo.ps, overwriting any earlier metademo.ps file created by the source.\
\
TeXShop assumes that one of the beginfig() numbers is negative, and thus that a file named metademo.ps will be generated by MetaPost. TeXShop then calls epstopdf to convert this postscript file to a pdf file, and displays the resulting pdf file. If no beginfig parameter is negative, MetaPost will run to completion without error, but TeXShop will display an error when it tries to convert metademo.ps to a pdf file.\
\
When you are editing a MetaPost file, change the number of the figure being edited from positive to negative. TeXShop will then display this figure as it is being debugged. When you are satisfied with this figure, change its number back to positive and change the number of another figure from positive to negative.\
\
TeXShop can convert postscript files like metademo.2 to pdf, but first these files must be renamed metademo.2.ps so TeXShop will recognize that they are postscript files. \
\
Once MetaPost files have been created, then can be displayed like any other illustration. Pdflatex can be used if the illustrations are converted to pdf form, or TeX and Ghostscript can be used to include the postscript illustrations without conversion. For example, the four illustrations created by the above MetaPost file can be displayed by typesetting the following file with TeX and Ghostscript:\
\
\pard\tx560\tx1940\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li1040\ql\qnatural

\f3\fs20 \cf0 	\\documentclass[11pt] \{article\}\
	\\usepackage\{graphicx\}\
\
	\\begin\{document\}\
\
	Here are some illustrations.\
	\\vspace\{.2in\}\
\
	\\includegraphics[width=1cm]\{metademo.1\}\
	\\hfill\
	\\includegraphics[width=1cm]\{metademo.2\}\
	\\hfill\
	\\includegraphics[width=1cm]\{metademo.3\}\
	\\hfill\
	\\includegraphics[width=1cm]\{metademo.4\}\
	\\hfill\
\
	\\end\{document\}\
\
\pard\tx560\tx1940\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li1040\ql\qnatural

\f0\b\fs24 \cf0 Plist Files:\
\
\pard\tx560\tx1940\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li1040\ql\qnatural

\f2\b0 \cf0 Mac OS X makes extensive use of xml files; xml is a structured language closely related to html. \
\
TeXShop uses three xml files for configuration: completion.plist, autocompletion.plist, and KeyEquivalents.plist. Copies of these files are in the TeXShop distribution folder. If you do not have this folder, you can retrieve a copy of the files from TeXShop itself. Hold down the command key and click on the TeXShop icon. A menu will appear; choose "Show Package Contents." A folder will appear. Search through various subfolders until you find the files. Copy them to the desktop by dragging them while holding down the option key. Be sure to leave the originals behind in the TeXShop folder!\
\
These files are used to configure the Latex Panel, Auto Completion, and the Keyboard Menu Shortcuts. Details are given elsewhere in this document. \
\
Files of type plist are ordinary text files, so they can be opened and edited with TeXShop, TextEdit, or other text editors. Editing the file is straightforward, but somewhat tedious.\
\
If you installed the Developer distribution of Mac OS X and you double click a .plist file, it will open in a program named Property List Editor. This program is useful for editing plist files, but it is buggy and does not display all file information. In particular, comments are missing. It is better to use TeXShop.\
\
\pard\tx560\tx1940\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li1040\ql\qnatural

\f0\b \cf0 Auto Completion:\
\
\pard\tx560\tx1940\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\li1040\ql\qnatural

\f2\b0 \cf0 Greg Landweber has added auto completion to the TeXShop editor. Typing a double quote will produce a pair of double quotes with the cursor positioned between them. Typing the ^ symbol will produce ^\{  \}  with the cursor positioned between the brackets. Etc. Thirty-nine such completions are currently available.\
\
Auto completion can be turned off or on with a preference item. The default preference is off. To try auto completion, turn it on.\
\
Auto completion is user configurable. The TeXShop distribution folder contains a file called "autocompletion.plist". To configure autocompletion, find the folder ~/Library/TeXShop and add a new folder named ~/Library/TeXShop/Keyboard. Place a copy of autocompletion.plist in this folder. Then edit the file to redefine Landweber's choices and add your own. You can examine the autocompletion.plist file to find a complete list of the default completions. \
\
See the earlier section on plist files for details.
\f0\b \
\
